{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17511733","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17511733"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:44:51+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:44:51+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11775"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11775","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11775"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.51,0.25,0.14,0.05,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4388"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103675"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4388","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4388"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11775"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86092"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"457"},{"type":"tags","id":"1139"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6805"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11370"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12300"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14844"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35920"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103675","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/103675"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 42-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a one-week history of feeling generally unwell, with fevers and sweats. Two days ago he began to get pain in his upper abdomen. He has no significant medical history except for an episode of diarrhoea one month ago when he was on holiday in Bali. He takes no regular medications. He drinks two glasses of wine a day and does not smoke. On examination, his pulse rate is 100/min, blood pressure 110/70 mmHg, and temperature 37.8\u00b0C. The physical examination demonstrates only some tenderness in the right upper quadrant. A CT scan is performed (Image). An Entamoeba serology test is positive.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate plan of management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Metronidazole","Percutaneous aspiration","Laparoscopic drainage","Entecavir","Laparotomy and segmental hepatic resection"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EWhat can be concluded from the clinical picture and the CT findings of a single peripherally enhancing lesion is that the patient has a liver abscess. The aetiology of a liver abscesses can be either pyogenic (bacterial), ameobic or fungal. Typically pyogenic and fungal abscesses have multiple abscesses, and amoebic abscesses tend to present with a single abscess only. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOverall, most liver abscesses have a pyogenic origin and of these, the biliary tract will be the prime source of infection. Patients would be screened with suspicious serology and stool testing to assist in diagnosis. Other conditions such diverticulitis and appendicitis can be complicated by haematogenous spread to the liver and abscess formation. However based on the history of recent diarrhoeal illness after travelling in an endemic area for amoebiasis (entamoeba histolytica) and CT findings of a single lesion, it is most likely that the patient has an amoebic abscess. With a positive entamoeba serology test, this is almost certainly an amoebic abscess.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003EEntamoeba histolytica\u003C/em\u003E (amoebiasis)\u003C/strong\u003E is found globally and is transmitted by faeco-oral contact. Most infections usually remain symptom-free, but patients can present 8 - 20 weeks later after travelling in an endemic area with right upper quadrant pain, fever, diarrhoea or less commonly jaundice.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn amoebic abscess would be treated first with \u003Cstrong\u003Emetronidazole\u003C/strong\u003E and close surveillance after confirmation on amoebiasis serology and stool testing. It should be noted that antibodies may be negative for the first seven days of illness, and positive antibodies may show a previous infection rather than confirmation of a current infection. Similarly, stool microscopy for amoebiasis may be falsely negative and takes time to show a positive result.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPercutaneous aspiration\u003C/strong\u003E is not recommended first-line treatment for ameobic liver abscess. It is reserved for non-responsive cases after treatment with antibiotics, or if there is a high risk of abscess rupture. This would be usually done via ultrasound-guided rather than CT-guided or surgical drainage. If the lesion was more suspicious for a pyogenic abscess on CT and history, then percutanous aspiration for both source control, organism identification and antibiotic guidance would be the priority.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEntecavir\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as this is an antiviral for treatment of hepatitis B - though it is endemic to Indonesia. Acute Hepatitis B infection present similarly with abdominal pain and diarrhoea with an incubation period (60 - 150 days), but likely would also present with fatigue, jaundice, fever or anorexia. Hepatomegaly and periportal oedema may be seen on CT, however the lesion seen in this case is not consistent.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELaparoscopic drainage or laparotomy and segmental hepatic resection \u003C/strong\u003Eare more invasive options that are not first-line for a simple liver abscess in an otherwise well patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Metronidazole is primary treatment for amoebic abscesses.","Percutaneous aspiration is reserved for amoebic abscesses non-responsive to antibiotic treatment, at high risk of rupture, or for pyogenic abscesses."],"references":["Roediger R. Lisker-Melman M. Pyogenic and Amebic Infections of the Liver. Gastroenterol Clin N Am 2020; 49:361\u201377","Anesi JA, Gluckman S. Amebic liver abscess. Clinical Liver Disease (Hoboken). 2015 Aug 24;6(2):41-43. doi: 10.1002/cld.488","Morgan M, Kogan J, Bell D, et al. Acute hepatitis. Reference article, Radiopaedia.org (Accessed on 31 Aug 2024) Available at: https://radiopaedia.org/articles/acute-hepatitis","Cooney J, Siakavellas SI, Chiodini PL, et al. Recent advances in the diagnosis and management of\u00a0amoebiasis. Front Gastroenterol 2025; 16:37-50"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86092"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11775"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"16393"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"16393","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/16393"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/0df8b1bc-bfcc-4887-8dcf-af2c561de691.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/0df8b1bc-bfcc-4887-8dcf-af2c561de691.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":587,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86092","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/86092"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-25T16:15:43+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-25T16:16:24+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4388"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103675"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description"